# Monthly Recurring Revenue (MRR)

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Description:'}) %>
Monthly Recurring Revenue shows how much revenue you collected from subscriptions.

There are several variations of MRR, like
<%= link_to 'Committed MRR  (CMRR)', '/saas-metrics/cmrr.html' %>.
It is non-GAAP metric, so analytics apps may calculate it differently.
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Use:'}) %>
Assess SaaS business month-to-month performance.
Calculate all other SaaS metrics.
Calculate recurring profit. Create projections to estimate future performance.
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Why we need it:'}) %>
When different length subscriptions are offered, bookkeeping stops reflecting true business performance. MRR
<%= link_to 'normalizes the revenue', '/saas-metrics/normalized-revenue.html' %> so that the time aspect of subscriptions becomes visible.
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Affects:'}) %>
All SaaS metrics
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Formula:'}) %>
No single formula. How FirstOfficer.io calculates MRR is explained in
<%= link_to 'Calculation Principles', '/docs/analytics_calculation_principles.html' %>
 article.
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Variations:'}) %>
Some businesses choose to include recurring but non-contracted revenue to MRR.
They then use term Contracted MRR to denote the real MRR which excludes any single purchases.
FirstOfficer.io only includes contracted revenue to MRR.
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>

<%= partial(:cheat_column_start, :locals => { :text => 'Also Called:'}) %>
Contracted Monthly Recurring Revenue.
<%= partial 'cheat_column_end' %>
